The '''Raymond Horton-Smith Prize''' is a prize awarded by the [[School of Clinical Medicine, University of Cambridge]] for the best [[thesis]] presented for [[Doctor of Medicine|MD]] degree during the academical year. Known as the prize for the best MD of the year,<ref>{{cite web|title=Aylward Bill|url=http://www.esaso.org/faculty/aylward-bill|work=ESASO - European School for Advanced Studies in Ophthalmology|publisher=Università della Svizzera italiana|accessdate=19 February 2012}}</ref> it should be awarded annually but from time to time it has not been awarded for some years.<ref name=NAW>{{cite journal|title=Universities and Colleges|work=BMJ|pmc=2285981}}</ref>
Often the prize has been considered to have a high prestige value since it has encouraged the Doctor of Medicine graduates ([[Doctor of Medicine|MD]]) of the world-renowned university to write the best thesis among them.<ref name=FRA>{{cite book|last=Mayo|first=Oliver|title=Fifty years of human genetics|coauthors=Carolyn Leach|year=2007|publisher=Wakefield Press|location=Kent Town, SA|isbn=978-1-86254-753-7|pages=149|url=http://books.google.it/books?id=tKW8TTwfmzUC&pg=PA149}}</ref><ref name=RCP>{{cite web|title=Munks Roll Details for Ian Michael Pudsey Dawson|url=http://munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk/Biography/Details/1204|work=RCP Munks Roll|accessdate=19 February 2012}}</ref>

==Founder==
'''Richard Horton Horton-Smith''', [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge_and_Dublin)|MA]], [[Queen's_Counsel|KC]] (4 December 1831 – 2 November 1919<ref>{{cite web|last=Patricia-M-Platten|title=The Platten's of Woolwich: Information about Richard Horton Smith|url=http://familytreemaker.genealogy.com/users/p/l/a/Patricia-M-Platten/WEBSITE-0001/UHP-0821.html|work=Genealogy.com|accessdate=19 February 2012}}</ref>)  was a [[barrister]] and a [[Masonic Lodge Officers|Masonic Lodge Officer]]. Before to be a student and later a [[Fellow#Cambridge and Oxford Colleges|Fellow]] at [[St John's College, Cambridge]], he attended also the University College School and the University College in London. His studies was about classics and law, becoming Classical Lecturer at [[King's College London]]. At the [[Lincoln's Inn]], London, he was [[Call to the Bar|called to the Bar]] in 1859, becoming Queen's Counsel ([[Queen's Counsel|KC]]) in 1877, [[Bencher]] in 1881, [[Trustee]] in 1884, Governor of Tancred's Charities in 1889, and [[Treasurer]] in 1903. He was member and officer of many [[Masonic Lodges]] (the Scientific Lodge, Cambridge, was his first one in 1856), becoming Life Governor of the [[Royal Masonic Benevolent Institution]], and also founding a lodge in 1893 (the Chancery Bar Lodge). He obtained his highest rank of Past Grand Registrar of England in 1898.<ref name=BIO>{{cite book|last=Anonymous|title=Representative British Freemasons|year=2003|publisher=Kessinger Publishing|location=Whitefish, MT|isbn=978-0-7661-3589-5|pages=117|url=http://books.google.it/books?id=6DtvwH_Dfl8C&pg=PA131}}</ref><br />

He was author of many books and articles (with John Peter De Gex he wrote the book ''Arrangements between Debtors and Creditors under the Bankruptcy Act, 1861'')<ref>{{cite web|title=Richard Horton Smith|url=http://www.google.com/search?hl=it&tbo=p&tbm=bks&q=inauthor:%22Richard+Horton+Smith%22|work=Google Books|accessdate=19 February 2012}}</ref> and was also Honorable Counsel to the [[Royal Philharmonic Society]], Director of the [[Royal Academy of Music]], and Vice-President of the Bar Musical Society.<ref name=BIO /><br />

He had three sons and two daughters.<ref name=BIO /> His third son Raymond John Horton-Smith (16 March 1873 – 8 Oct 1899), who studied medicine at several universities including the [[St John's College, Cambridge]], gaining [[MB BCh]], [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge_and_Dublin)|MA]], [[Membership of the Royal College of Surgeons|MRCS]], [[LRCP]] and achieving brilliant results (Wainwright Prizeman at University of London), died of tuberculosis at [[Davos]], Switzerland, aged 27.<ref>{{cite web|title=Horton-Smith, Raymond John (1873-1899 )|url=http://www.aim25.ac.uk/cgi-bin/vcdf/detail?coll_id=7368&inst_id=6|work=AIM25|accessdate=2004}}</ref> Some months later, in 1900, Richard Horton-Smith found the Raymond Horton-Smith Prize in his honour, communicating to the [[University of Cambridge#Senate and the Regent House|Council of the Senate]] (University of Cambridge) his offer of a fund of 500 pounds for his proposed prize, which was approved on 16 March 1900.<ref>{{cite book|last=Clark|first=John Willis|title=Endowments of the University of Cambridge|year=1904|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|pages=434–435|url=http://www.archive.org/stream/endowmentsunive00clargoog#page/n460/mode/2up}}</ref> Later, moneys for the Raymond Horton-Smith Fund would be given also by his son Sir Percival Horton-Smith Hartley, and by his granddaughter Mrs. A. G. Wornum.<ref name=STA>{{cite web|title=Raymond Horton-Smith Prize|url=http://www.admin.cam.ac.uk/univ/so/2011/chapter12-section2.html#heading2-237|work=Statutes and Ordinances of the University of Cambridge|publisher=University of Cambridge|accessdate=2011}}</ref>

==Eligibility and criteria==
The candidates for the degree of Doctor of Medicine ([[Doctor of Medicine|MD]]) present their MD Thesis or a dissertation for the MD of the academical year at the [[University of Cambridge]]. A committee judge the best thesis or dissertation among the candidates, possibly consulting one independent referee, possibly paying him through a fee approved by the [[Cambridge University Council]].<ref name=STA />

==Award value==
The value of the Prize is the net annual income of the Raymond Horton-Smith Fund deducting a possible fee (to pay a referee) and the price to purchase a book selected with the prize-winner but approved by the [[Vice-Chancellor of the University of Cambridge|Vice-Chancellor]] and to be stamped with the arms of the university and with the Horton-Smith armorial bearings.<ref name=STA />

